In TypeScript, you can use the `as` keyword to explicitly specify the type of a value, even if you're not sure about its type at the time of declaration. This is called [type assertion](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/2/everyday-types.html#type-assertions).

Here's an example:

```typescript
let value: any;

// In practice, you know that `value` will always be a string.
value = "Hello, world!";

// TypeScript doesn't know this, so it considers `value` to be of type `any`.
// You can use type assertion to tell TypeScript that `value` is actually a string.

const stringifiedValue = value as string;

// Now, TypeScript knows that `stringifiedValue` is a string.
console.log(stringifiedValue);
```

### Notes:

- **Type assertion** is a way to inform TypeScript that you are aware of the type of a value, even if it's not explicitly declared.
- **Type assertion does not change the actual type of the value**. It only affects how TypeScript interprets the code.
- **Type assertion is useful when you're working with APIs that return values of unknown types**.

### Additional Resources:

- [TypeScript Handbook: Type Assertions](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/2/everyday-types.html#type-assertions)
- [TypeScript Handbook: Type Guards](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/2/generics.html#type-guards-and-type-assertions)

